Headlines.Author: Saabira Chaudhuri
Headlines.Headline: Exceed Gets Going-Private Offer Valuing It at $57 Million

PARAGRAPH.#text: Exceed Co. EDS said it has received an offer to be taken private by its chief executive and his affiliates in a deal valuing the sportswear company at around $57 million. CEO Shuipan Lin and his affiliates, including Tiancheng Int'l Investment Group Ltd., HK Haima Group Ltd., Wisetech Holdings Ltd., Windtech Holdings Ltd. and RichWise International Investment Group Ltd., have offered to buy all the shares they don't already own for $1.72 a share, a 15% premium over Friday's close. As of Saturday, the CEO and his affiliates owned close to 67% of Exceed.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Exceed Gets Going-Private Offer Valuing It at $57 Million

Headlines.Author: Ben Fox
Headlines.Headline: Exceed 1Q Net Up 3.1% on Footwear Sales; Sees Weaker 2Q, FY Rev

PARAGRAPH.#text: Exceed Co.'s EDS first-quarter earnings rose 3.1% as the China-based apparel company saw footwear revenue jump, compensating for lighter accessory and apparel sales. But Exceed warned that macroeconomic headwinds in China contributed to softer consumer demand for sportswear products, forcing its distributors to adopt a more conservative approach to the second half of 2012. It said it expects to face "a challenging demand environment" for the rest of the year. As a result, the company forecast second-quarter revenue of CNY482.0 million to CNY519.0 million, a drop of 30% to 35% from a year earlier.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Exceed 1Q Net Up 3.1% on Footwear Sales; Sees Weaker 2Q, FY Rev

Headlines.Author: Joan E. Solsman
Headlines.Headline: Exceed Names Finance Executive Tai As New CFO; Shares Fall

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Exceed Co. EDS promoted finance executive Vivien Tai to the role of chief financial officer, as her predecessor Terence Wong departs the sportswear company "to pursue another professional opportunity," it said Wednesday in a release. Shares in the Chinese company were down 7% at $3.47 in light after-hours trading. Through the close, the company's stock has fallen 55% so far this year, deeper than the wider market's decline. The company has been plagued by accusations about the accuracy of its financial and operational disclosures.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Exceed Names Finance Executive Tai As New CFO; Shares Fall

Headlines.Author: Tess Stynes
Headlines.Headline: Exceed CEO Again Attempts To Reassure Investors

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Exceed Co.'s EDS chief executive, Shuipan Lin, again addressed shareholder concerns about its operations, this time saying the sportswear company has asked its board's audit committee to discuss ways to improve the reporting system of its Xidelong retail-store network. Shares were down 6.1% at $4 in recent trading. They are down 51% this year, including a 9% drop this month. It is the second time this month the Chinese company's CEO has sent a letter to shareholders to assure investors that concerns about the company's financial and operations disclosures were unwarranted.

Headlines.Author: Drew FitzGerald
Headlines.Headline: Exceed 2Q Profit Up 5.2% On Apparel Sales

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Exceed Co.'s EDS second-quarter earnings rose 5.2% as the sportswear manufacturer reported stronger revenue, especially in its apparel business. Looking to the current quarter, the China-based company forecast revenue between CNY1.01 billion and CNY1.02 billion, which represents 21% to 23% sales growth. Analysts polled by Thomson Reuters were expecting 21% growth. American depositary shares were up 8.3%, at $4.95 after hours, amid better-than-expected results. They were still off 35% over the past year through the close.

Headlines.Author: John Kell
Headlines.Headline: Exceed Co. Attempts To Assure Investors Of Disclosures Accuracy

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES A letter to shareholders written by Exceed Co. Ltd.'s EDS Chairman and Chief Executive Shuipan Lin sought to assure investors that concerns about the Chinese sportswear maker's financial and operational disclosure are unwarranted. Still, shares slid 9.5% to $4.48 in recent trading. In the letter, Lin said the company maintains "a high level of transparency and disclosure, and our financial position and operations remain strong." He contended the accusations were levied by short sellers who seek to financially benefit by a decline in Exceed's stock price.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Exceed Co. Attempts To Assure Investors Of Disclosures Accuracy
